17 SECTION 3. The North Carolina Board of Dental Examiners shall adopt temporary
18 rules to implement the provisions of Sections 1 and 2 of this act and shall adopt permanent rules
19 to replace the temporary rules. Those temporary rules shall remain in effect until permanent rules
20 that replace those rules become effective.
21 SECTION 4.(a) G.S. 93B-5(g) reads as rewritten:
22 "(g) Within six months of a board member's initial appointment to the board, and at least
23 once within every two calendar years thereafter, a board member shall receive training, either
24 from the board's staff, including its legal advisor, or from an outside educational institution such
25 as the School of Government of the University of North Carolina, on the statutes governing the
26 board and rules adopted by the board, as well as the following State and federal laws, in order to
27 better understand the obligations and limitations of a State agency:
28 (1) Chapter 150B, The Administrative Procedure Act.
29 (2) Chapter 132, The Public Records Law.
30 (3) Article 33C of Chapter 143, The Open Meetings Act.
31 (4) Articles 31 and 31A of Chapter 143, The State Tort Claims Act and The
32 Defense of State Employees Law.
33 (5) Chapter 138A, The State Government Ethics Act.
34 (6) Chapter 120C, Lobbying.
35 (7) Antitrust law and State action immunity.
36 Completion of the training requirements contained in Chapter 138A and Chapter 120C of the
37 General Statutes satisfies the requirements of subdivisions (5) and (6) of this subsection."
38 SECTION 4.(b) Chapter 93B of the General Statutes is amended by adding six new
39 sections to read:
40 "§ 93B-17. Occupational licensing board rulemaking.
41 (a) Each occupational licensing board shall adopt rules for the receipt and resolution of
42 complaints, for taking disciplinary or enforcement actions against its licensees, and for taking
43 enforcement actions against persons not licensed by the board.
44 (b) Any interpretation, clarification, or other delineation of the scope of practice of an
45 occupational licensing board shall be adopted as a rule.
46 "§ 93B-18. Unlicensed activity.
47 (a) An occupational licensing board shall have the authority to investigate unlicensed
48 activity and notify unlicensed persons and entities of the possible violation of the law and
49 administrative rules and any civil action or criminal penalty that may be imposed by a court. The
50 notification shall not indicate that the occupational licensing board has made any finding of a
51 violation but may indicate the board's belief or opinion that a particular act may violate the
Page 4 DRH50026-DCz-1A

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 board's enabling statutes, include factual information regarding legislation and court proceedings
2 concerning the potential violation, and provide notice of the board's intention to pursue
3 administrative remedies or court proceedings with regard to the potential violation.
4 (b) Any occupational licensing board providing notification to unlicensed persons and
5 entities of a possible violation of the law and administrative rules and any civil action or criminal
6 penalty that may be imposed by a court shall include the following statement in the notification:
7
8 You are hereby notified that the opinion expressed herein is not a legal
9 determination. An occupational licensing board does not have the authority to
10 order you to discontinue your current practices. Only a court may determine that
11 you have violated or are violating any law and, if appropriate, impose a remedy
12 or penalty for the violation. Further, pursuant to G.S. 150B-4, you may have the
13 right, prior to initiation of any court action by the occupational licensing board,
14 to request a declaratory ruling regarding whether your particular conduct is
15 lawful. You are further notified that any right to a declaratory ruling supplements
16 any other legal rights that you may already have to establish the legality of your
17 conduct with respect to the goods or services you offer or provide.
18
19 "§ 93B-19. Venue for court enforcement.
20 The venue for occupational licensing boards seeking court orders for injunctive relief or to
21 show cause for failure to comply with a subpoena lawfully issued by the occupational licensing
22 board shall be in the superior court of the county where the defendant resides or in the county
23 where the occupational licensing board has its principal place of business.
24 "§ 93B-20. Injunctive relief.
25 An occupational licensing board may appear in its own name in superior court in actions for
26 injunctive relief to restrain the violation of the provisions of a statute administered by the board
27 or a rule or order of the board. The superior court shall have the jurisdiction to grant these
28 injunctions, restraining orders, or take other appropriate action even if criminal prosecution has
29 been or may be instituted as a result of the violations, or whether the person is a licensee of the
30 board. No board shall issue such orders independently of the superior court unless specifically
31 authorized to do so by law.
32 "§ 93B-21. Jurisdictional disputes between boards.
33 It is the policy of the State that jurisdictional disputes among occupational licensing boards
34 shall be resolved through informal procedures. If a jurisdictional dispute among occupational
35 licensing boards cannot be resolved through informal procedures, any affected board may
36 commence an administrative proceeding to resolve the jurisdictional dispute by filing a petition
37 with the Office of Administrative Hearings and serve the petition on all affected boards. Once
38 the petition is filed and the required fee is paid, the dispute shall become a contested case and
39 shall be conducted by the Office of Administrative Hearings under Articles 3 and 4 of Chapter
40 150B of the General Statutes.
41 "§ 93B-22. Complaint process.
42 Each occupational licensing board shall develop and implement a complaint process that
43 provides for all of the following:
44 (1) A description of the complaint process on the board's website, including the
45 types of violations that are under the jurisdictional authority of the board.
46 (2) Electronic complaint submission via the board's website, including a
47 prominently displayed link to a complaint form.
48 (3) The ability to provide complainants with a written description of the final
49 disposition of each complaint."
